posts.name: Fletch
posts.cooked:
Can you provide more details? Whats not working? How? What should it be doing that it’s not? What shouldn’t it be doing but is?

Edit: is the code on a different branch? When i open that link on my phone (main branch), you don’t have an autonomous command defined anywhere at all. In fact, RobotContainer::getAutonomousCommand() explicitly returns null

posts.name: Evan
posts.cooked: What is happening is that when we go to run autonomous. The bot will run for less than a second and then not run again until we get completely out of driver station. What we want to happen is have the bot run for a few seconds and then stop. Our Autonomous code is in drive.java and in RobotContainer in our code we have it set to return m_drive.LeftBlue() we just forgot to have the changed in github and I just updated that.

posts.name: Fletch
posts.cooked: I think the issue is that you’re simply stopping/starting the timer, not resetting or restarting.  So when you test for autoTimer.hasElapsed(1) is succeeds, but when you run hasElapsed(0.5) in the next block, it’s already past that so it skips instantly.

posts.name: Fletch
posts.cooked:
Actually, looking again, you have everything as its own unbounded command in composed sequential groups.

andThen(...) accepts a list of commands to run sequentially after the command you’re calling it from.  Then each run(...) should create a command that will run indefinitely until interrupted

posts.name: Jonathan Zimmerman
posts.cooked:
I think you need to go back and look at the Timer.hasElapsed() documentation. It won’t wait for the specified time. Instead it returns immediately indicating if the specified amount of time has elapsed.

From my read of your code all of the andThen groups will run and complete almost immediately.
